<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<FindBugsFilter xmlns="https://github.com/spotbugs/filter/3.0.0">
  <!--
    Reviewed suppressions (Chapter 16: suppress with a reason, never disable a whole detector).

    The module's own hand-written classes need NO suppression: the value types are immutable records,
    the pricing services hold no exposed mutable representation, and the metric counters use
    thread-safe primitives. That is the chapter's point, made by the build.

    The first entry is scoped to JMH's machine-generated harness. JMH's annotation processor
    (jmh-generator-annprocess) emits synthetic benchmark driver classes into the
    org.acme.performance.jmh_generated package at build time. That generated bytecode is not authored
    by the book, so holding it to the house ruleset would report findings on code we did not write.
    The exclusion is by generated package only; every detector stays enabled, and every hand-written
    class in org.acme.performance is fully analysed.

    The second entry is the chapter's teaching beat made literal. PricingBenchmark.measureWrong() is
    the deliberately-lying benchmark: it calls a pure method and discards the result, so the JIT may
    eliminate the work (dead-code elimination). SpotBugs correctly flags exactly that shape
    (RV_RETURN_VALUE_IGNORED_NO_SIDE_EFFECT) — static analysis catches the broken benchmark, which is
    the point. The finding is suppressed here, narrowly and with this reason, so the demonstration of
    the anti-pattern can stand in the source beside the honest version; the detector stays enabled for
    every other method, and measureRight() / measureTwoResults() show the fix.
  -->
  <Match>
    <Package name="~org\.acme\.performance\.jmh_generated.*"/>
  </Match>
  <Match>
    <Class name="org.acme.performance.PricingBenchmark"/>
    <Method name="measureWrong"/>
    <Bug pattern="RV_RETURN_VALUE_IGNORED_NO_SIDE_EFFECT"/>
  </Match>
</FindBugsFilter>
